Our `w-*`, `h-*`, and `max-h-*` utilities all include our spacing scale which has various values across the range of 0–96 (from `0rem` up to `24rem`). However, our utilities for `min-w-*`, `min-h-*`, and `max-w-*` did not include these values. This leads to an inconsistent experience when using these utilities and this PR aims to fix those.

Now you can write utilities like `min-w-32`,`min-h-3`, or `max-w-48` and get the following as you would expect:

```css
.min-h-3 {
  min-height: 0.75rem;
}
.min-w-32 {
  min-width: 8rem;
}
.max-w-48 {
  max-width: 12rem;
}
```

Here we're adding `-webkit-tap-highlight-color: transparent;` to disable tap highlights on iOS.

This means that the brief gray overlay that appears when tapping links or buttons will not anymore.

**Before**

https://github.com/tailwindlabs/tailwindcss/assets/614993/1b2a6d27-5f51-4a1d-a7e9-7382ba25a48e

**After**

https://github.com/tailwindlabs/tailwindcss/assets/614993/14c4b101-474a-4d6a-9de4-6d29e0620d80


If you want to re-enable the tap highlight in your own project you can do so by adding a rule to revert it to the original value:

```css
@layer base {
  html,
  :host {
    -webkit-tap-highlight-color: revert;
  }
}
```

This PR adds a `size-*` utility that sets both `width` and `height`.

The supported values are the same as the `w-*` and `h-*` utilities with the exception of screen units (`screen`, `svh`, `lvh`, `dvh`, `svw`, `lvw`, and `dvw`).

Now you can write this:
```html
<div class="size-12"></div>
```

And it will generate the following css:
```css
.size-12 {
  width: 3rem;
  height: 3rem;
}
```
